The sun., April 30, 1916, FIFTH SECTION LITHOGRAVURE SUPPLEMENT, Image 51
  <a href="http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030272/1916-04-30/ed-1/seq-51/" rel="nofollow">chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030272/1916-04-30/ed-...</a>
is a page of photos of lovely ladies with dogs --the Pampered Pets of the Stars of the Stage and Screen
Bonnie Glass is bottom center with her &quot;scotch hound.&quot;

<a href="http://www.streetswing.com/histmai2/d2bglass.htm" rel="nofollow">www.streetswing.com/histmai2/d2bglass.htm</a>
has some biographical information, beginning, &quot;Bonnie Glass was another very talented and successful dancer in vaudeville Theaters during the 1910s. Started her career as a Musical Comedy soloist, she found she had a knack for dancing. &quot;
&quot;Glass would partner many future movie stars such as Clifton Webb (1914) and Valentino (1915.) &quot;

More info and links to pictures at 
<a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/puzzlemaster/6010768740/" title="Helen Roche aka Bonnie Glass aka Mrs Ben Ali Haggan 1923 by puzzlemaster, on Flickr"><img src="http://farm7.staticflickr.com/6143/6010768740_646ac4c178_m.jpg" width="201" height="240" alt="Helen Roche aka Bonnie Glass aka Mrs Ben Ali Haggan 1923" /></a>
uploaded by Flickr user Puzzlemaster who indicates that she was born &quot;Helen Roche.&quot;

Her marriage to Ben Ali Haggin was revealed in the NYT of June 5, 1916
  <a href="http://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F60B12F63E5E13738DDDAC0894DE405B868DF1D3" rel="nofollow">query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F60B12F63E5E13738...</a>
&quot;BEN ALI HAGGIN WEDS MISS BONNIE GLASS; Artist Who inherited $10,000,000 Admits He Was Quietly Married to Actress. HE WAS RECENTLY DIVORCED Friends Did Not Know That His First Wife Had obtained a Decree.&quot;

Her entry in Dictionary of Women Worldwide: 25,000 Women Through the Ages 
[available through HighBeam Research at <a href="http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G2-2588809191.html" rel="nofollow">www.highbeam.com/doc/1G2-2588809191.html</a> but the full article needs a subscription]
reveals &quot;American exhibition ballroom dancer. Born Helen Roche, c. 1895, in Roxbury, Massachusetts; m. Graham Glass, 1911 (div. 1914); m. Ben Ali Haggin (society painter), c. 1915.   Appeared as theatrical ballet dancer at roof garden theaters in New York City as a teenager (c. 1910); had brief marriage to Oregon millionaire, closely followed in local press (1911–14); made 1st appearance as Bonnie Glass … &quot;
